  abstract = {This paper surveys and evaluates J.L. Ericksen’s fundamental work in developing, refining, promoting, and solving problems for Cosserat theories of rods and shells. These geometrically and mechanically exact nonlinear theories can be used to describe physically important effects not accounted for by their classical predecessors. This paper begins with a sketch of early theories of the mechanics of rods and shells. It then gives a critical account of the pioneering and immediately influential 1958 paper Ericksen wrote with C. Truesdell. It next describes Ericksen’s subsequent contributions to the formulation and analysis of specific problems for these Cosserat theories, and how they resolved some open issues. This paper concludes with a discussion of refinements of these theories and a commentary on their modern roles.},
