  abstract = {The application of GFRP bars requires a familiar safety concept based on reliably determined long-term values. Therefore, the effect of different exposure conditions and their synergism on mechanical and durability properties needs to be considered. This paper presents experimental and analytical investigations about the permanent tensile resistance of GFRP bars in concrete environment. For comparison, specimens were exposed to alkaline environment and/or moisture at elevated stress levels to accelerate the effect of real life conditions. To predict the long-term behavior within reasonable test durations the timetemperature superposition principle was applied by obtaining creep curves at temperatures of 23°C (room temperature), 40°C and 60°C. The results indicated that the durability and damage mechanism of the bars were affected by alkalinity and moisture. As a conclusion, the interaction of the particular expositions seems to be significant and needs to be assessed.},
